INFORMATION
##############################################

FlameGPU 1.5.0 requires CUDA, which is not automatically loaded.
Choose a version that suits the graphics card you are using like so:

$ module avail cuda
cuda/6.5         cuda/7.5.18      cuda/9.0.176     cuda/9.2.148
cuda/7.0         cuda/8.0.61      cuda/9.1.85      cuda/9.2.88.1

$ module load cuda/9.2.148

Once CUDA is loaded, you can run the utilities. Since FlameGPU reuses filenames
for both the Console and Visualisation branches, you may need to specify full filepaths.

If you're interested in just the CONSOLE operation, the filename alone will suffice, e.g.,
$ Boids_Partitioning

If you're interested in the VISUALISATION functionality, you will need to specify the path:
$ /packages/7x/flamegpu/1.5.0/bin/linux-x64/Release_Visualisation/Boids_Partitioning

In case you want to know all the available utilities:

$ ls /packages/7x/flamegpu/1.5.0/bin/linux-x64/Release_Console
$ ls /packages/7x/flamegpu/1.5.0/bin/linux-x64/Release_Visualisation


